<h3>The Question</h3>
<p>
    The <a href="/backlog/141-dev-browser-vision/">dev-browser vision (#141)</a> proposes a Chromium-based
    developer browser whose tooling <strong>lights up only on a standard-conformant app</strong> — depth
    scaling with how much of the standard the app implements. The rich vision is settled and the
    <strong>sequencing</strong> fork is ruled (extension/DevTools-panel first, browser later). What remains
    open are four design forks: the <strong>conformance-gate contract</strong>, the <strong>AI fix-loop
    guardrails</strong>, the <strong>commercial-license</strong> call, and the <strong>relationship to
    plateau-app</strong>. This survey grounds those forks in market prior art and the machinery already in the
    repo, so each rule reuses platform/precedent vocabulary instead of coining its own.
</p>

<h3>Recommendation (forks open in #141)</h3>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Gate on a capability manifest, degrade gracefully</strong> — the browser reads the same
        introspectable self-description the standard already exposes (registries, intents, contexts, traces,
        <code>capabilityMatrix</code>); each feature activates per-capability, not all-or-nothing, so a thinly
        conformant app still lights up the slice it supports.</li>
    <li><strong>Reuse the verify-gated autofix loop, default to PR-for-review</strong> — the AI fix loop is the
        existing <code>conformance-autofix</code> engine generalized to running apps: propose → apply →
        re-verify against the app's own declared rules/tests → keep only if it clears with no regression;
        autonomy is a configured level (report-only → propose → live-verify → open-PR), and live-patching a
        <em>deployed</em> app is session-only, revertible, and authorization-gated.</li>
    <li><strong>Yes, carry a commercial license (deferred)</strong> — a free tier (the panel = the funnel) →
        paid browser, per the cost-flat / open-core gradient; the browser runs locally so it never takes on
        server cost. The exact tier split is deferred to first-sale.</li>
    <li><strong>A distinct shell that reuses plateau-app's panels, not a fork of it</strong> — the
        Technical/Intent Configurators and the profile system already live in plateau-app; the browser embeds
        them as the management UI rather than re-implementing or absorbing the product.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Finding 1 — the only precedent is framework-gated; the novel move is standard-gated</h3>
<p>
    React / Vue / Redux DevTools <strong>detect their framework and only light up when present</strong> — but
    compatibility means <em>one specific framework</em>, the payoff is a single debug tab, and each tool only
    ever helps that framework's apps. Storybook/Ladle similarly light up only via authored stories. No product
    is a browser whose tooling depth scales with how <em>standard</em>-compliant the loaded app is (market scan
    found none). Gating on a <strong>vendor-neutral standard</strong> inverts framework lock-in into a portable
    contract: any conformant app — any stack — surfaces the same deep tooling through one browser.
</p>

<h3>Finding 2 — the conformance gate is a capability manifest, surfaced per-feature (grounds fork 1)</h3>
<p>
    The standard already ships the self-description the gate needs. <code>check:standards</code> is the
    build-time conformance suite; the runtime analogue is the introspectable registries plus the
    <a href="/protocols/">capability matrix</a> — a <strong>3-state tier map</strong> (native-ok / polyfill-ok
    / capability-hard) keyed off <code>capabilities.json</code>. The market parallel is a CI
    <strong>quality gate</strong> (SonarQube) reported as a status check: pass/fail per condition, with a
    warn-only mode before enforcement. The implication is the same here: the browser should read the app's
    declared conformance and <strong>activate each feature per-capability</strong> (graceful degradation), not
    treat the app as binary compatible/incompatible. Partial conformance lights up the partial surface.
</p>

<h3>Finding 3 — the AI fix loop already exists as a verify-gated engine (grounds fork 2)</h3>
<p>
    The repo's <code>conformance-autofix</code> agent is the exact loop the vision's analyst/QA fix story
    needs, one altitude down: <strong>propose a patch → apply → re-run the suite → keep only if the target
    failure cleared and no new error appeared, else revert</strong>. It is bounded (max-rounds backstop),
    metered (cap on model-fixer calls so a runaway loop can't burn a BYO key), and has a human-review hook that
    can revert a gate-passing patch before it lands. Generalizing it to a running app: the "suite" becomes the
    app's own declared rules + tests, and the gate is the same verify-then-keep-or-revert moat.
</p>
<p>
    Market prior art on autofix safety converges on the same shape: best practice requires
    <strong>passing tests + a re-scan before any PR is auto-opened</strong>, an autonomy ladder (assisted →
    semi-autonomous → autonomous) with confidence thresholds, an observation period that generates PRs without
    auto-merge, and a safety checklist in the PR body (tests run, files touched, <strong>revert plan</strong>).
    The riskiest capability — <strong>live-patching a deployed app</strong> — needs an explicit story:
    session-only patches, revertible, and an authorization gate on who may apply.
</p>

<h3>Finding 4 — local + free-tier-funnel is the cost-flat, open-core shape (grounds fork 3)</h3>
<p>
    The monetization principle is settled: open standard/impl are free; paid products are licensed; a local
    product <em>may</em> carry a commercial license where there's value. The dev browser is the textbook case —
    it <strong>runs locally</strong> (no server, no uptime), yet is product-shaped enough to charge for as a
    <strong>free tier → paid</strong> upgrade, with the extension/panel as the free funnel. The market confirms
    the pattern: 2026 dev tools lean on free tiers as evaluation, per-seat commercial licensing for teams, and
    open-core / BYO-key tiers (Cursor, Windsurf, Cline). The license <em>decision</em> is yes-in-principle but
    <strong>deferred</strong> to first-sale; only the tier caveats need settling then.
</p>

<h3>Finding 5 — plateau-app already owns the panels the browser would host (grounds fork 4)</h3>
<p>
    plateau-app already ships a <code>technical-configurator</code>, an <code>intent-configurator</code>, and a
    <code>profiles</code> system — the same persona/profile model the vision calls a "feature toggle map" over
    introspection surfaces. So the browser is not a new product that re-implements these, nor a fork of
    plateau-app: it is a <strong>distinct shell that embeds plateau-app's panels</strong> as its management UI.
    The browser owns the chrome-level capabilities a panel can't reach (intercepting navigation to show "not
    compatible," a full management UI outside the DevTools dock); plateau-app keeps owning the configurators
    and profiles.
</p>

<h3>Finding 6 — the sequencing fork is resolved (carried, not re-opened)</h3>
<p>
    <strong>Extension / DevTools-panel first, standalone browser later, Chromium fork as last resort.</strong>
    The panel is the cheapest proof of the "lights up on a conformant app" model <em>and</em> the free funnel;
    the browser becomes the paid product only when a capability demands chrome-level UI an extension can't
    reach; a fork stays a last resort (Replay.io shows a fork is heavy/ongoing). This was settled 2026-06-11 by
    the staged path + monetization and is <strong>not</strong> re-opened by the four forks below.
</p>

